<subSubSection lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,1599,2022]" lastBlockId="32.[151,1437,151,2007]" lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1599,1624]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Genus of the tribe Chthoniini with ephippiochthonian chela, chelal hand usually weakly depressed at level of trichobothria 
<emphasis box="[395,417,1635,1660]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">ib</emphasis>
/ 
<emphasis box="[424,457,1635,1660]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">isb</emphasis>
, distad of these trichobothria with a large, more or less prominent hump, followed by a continuous depression towards base of fixed finger, giving the dorsal contour a more or less marked step-like appearance in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[458,524,1707,1732]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1797,1820]" captionTargetBox="[183,1404,607,1740]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,588,1774]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Ephippiochthonius tetrachelatus (Preyssler, 1790) n. comb., chela of male from Královice-Hájek, U. Markéty, Prague, Czech Republic. 1, antiaxial view, slightly dorsal; 2, dorsal view; 3, ventral view. Abbreviations: ap: apodeme; as: antiaxial sensory setae; bc: basal condyle; ca: antiaxial condyle; cp: paraxial condyle; eh: edge; fa: antiaxial lyrifissure of fixed chelal finger; fb: basal lyrifissure of fixed chelal finger; fd 1, fd 2, fd 3: dorsal lyrifissures of the fixed chelal finger; hd: distal lyrifissure of chelal hand; hp: proximal lyrifissure of chelal hand; ip: intercondylar protuberance; ma 1, ma 2: antiaxial lyrifissures of movable chelal finger; mv 1, mv 2: ventral lyrifissures of movable chelal finger; sp: subdistal protuberance; td: accessory tooth." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/437612/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); without a ventral hollow before base of movable finger; base of chelal hand not abruptly constricted paraxially; prominent bow-like medial protuberance (
<emphasis box="[1012,1034,1744,1767]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">ip</emphasis>
) present between chelal condyles, slightly closer to the paraxial one; distal end of hand and bases of chelal fingers with strongly sclerotized condylar complex; proximal portion of chelal hand with only 3 setae in adults and tritonymphs, seta 
<emphasis box="[1230,1258,1815,1840]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">ph</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[1258,1266,1830,1844]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">3</emphasis>
lacking, usual chaetotaxy: 4:5:3 (
<figureCitation box="[359,460,1853,1878]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1797,1820]" captionTargetBox="[183,1404,607,1740]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,588,1774]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Ephippiochthonius tetrachelatus (Preyssler, 1790) n. comb., chela of male from Královice-Hájek, U. Markéty, Prague, Czech Republic. 1, antiaxial view, slightly dorsal; 2, dorsal view; 3, ventral view. Abbreviations: ap: apodeme; as: antiaxial sensory setae; bc: basal condyle; ca: antiaxial condyle; cp: paraxial condyle; eh: edge; fa: antiaxial lyrifissure of fixed chelal finger; fb: basal lyrifissure of fixed chelal finger; fd 1, fd 2, fd 3: dorsal lyrifissures of the fixed chelal finger; hd: distal lyrifissure of chelal hand; hp: proximal lyrifissure of chelal hand; ip: intercondylar protuberance; ma 1, ma 2: antiaxial lyrifissures of movable chelal finger; mv 1, mv 2: ventral lyrifissures of movable chelal finger; sp: subdistal protuberance; td: accessory tooth." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/437612/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Figs 1–3</figureCitation>
). Movable pedipalpal finger slightly shorter than the fixed; axis of fixed finger apically forming a slightly obtuse angle; both fingers mostly straight; dental rows homo- or heterodentate, bearing spaced, upright teeth, without saw-like dentition, third tooth of normal row (
<emphasis box="[929,957,1927,1950]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">mt</emphasis>
) of fixed finger not modified; tip of fixed finger with an accessory tooth (
<emphasis box="[504,526,1961,1986]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">td</emphasis>
) on antiaxial face; tip of fixed chelal finger of male, tritonymph and deutonymph with a deep hollow on paraxial face and a subapical protuberance (
<emphasis box="[900,925,1999,2022]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">sp</emphasis>
), latter lacking in female; coupled sensilla 
<emphasis box="[1409,1435,1999,2022]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">pc</emphasis>
usually between trichobothria 
<emphasis box="[493,518,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">sb</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[574,588,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">b</emphasis>
, rarely level with 
<emphasis box="[796,821,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">sb</emphasis>
or, exceptionally, distad of 
<emphasis box="[1135,1160,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">sb</emphasis>
; base of movable chelal finger with an enlarged sclerotized condyle (
<emphasis box="[668,695,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">bc</emphasis>
), followed by a long, well sclerotized apodeme. Lyrifissure 
<emphasis box="[1394,1428,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">ma</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[1428,1436,203,217]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">1</emphasis>
always present, 
<emphasis box="[336,370,228,251]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">ma</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[370,378,241,255]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">2</emphasis>
present or absent, depending of the species-groups concerned. Anterior margin of carapace more strongly dentate between median macrosetae, straight or weakly prominent, without a well-defined epistome. Coxae II and III with coxal spines; bisetose intercoxal tubercle present between coxae III and IV; distal marginal seta of pedipalpal coxal disk usually distinctly longer than distal marginal seta of coxa I, exceptionally of same length; Sternite III in males and females usually with 10 marginal setae (not counting stigmatal setae or setae bordering notch in male), of which the lateral one on each side is usually reduced to the size of a microseta (
<figureCitation box="[1354,1422,409,434]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 7" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1366,1389]" captionTargetBox="[198,1410,200,1356]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[154,1439,177,1392]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 7. Ephippiochthonius tetrachelatus (Preyssler, 1790) n. comb., males from Královice-Hájek, U. Markéty, Prague, Czech Republic (4 ‒ 6) and male from Sea Cliff, Nassau, New York, U. S. A. (7). 4, left chelicera; 5, external genital area; 6, basal portion of movable chelal finger; 7. Basal portions of chelal fingers. Abbreviations: ap: apodeme; bc: basal condyle; ca: antiaxial condyle; fo: fixed chelal finger foramen; ip: intercondylar protuberance; ls: lateral setae; ldb, ldst, ldt, lvb, lve, lvt: lyrifissures associated with cheliceral setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/437613/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Male genitalia without median hiatus between guard-setae. Comparison with related genera as in the key and 
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="18.[151,239,152,175]" captionTargetBox="[151,1425,266,1686]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="TABLE 1. Character states of Chthonius - related genera (those with coxal spines on coxae II and III). Abbreviations of genera: Cant., Cantabrochthonius; Ephip., Ephippiochthonius; Glob., Globochthonius; Hesp., Hesperochthonius; Micr., Microchthonius; Neo., Neochthonius; Occ., Occidenchthonius; Spelyng., Spelyngochthonius." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5E7F86FFAD5504FF5C41F9FBF5FF3D" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" tableUuid="DF5E7F86FFAD5504FF5C41F9FBF5FF3D">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
